Starbucks Capstone Challenge¶

Introduction¶

This data set contains simulated data that mimics customer behavior on the Starbucks rewards mobile app. Once every few days, Starbucks sends out an offer to users of the mobile app. An offer can be merely an advertisement for a drink or an actual offer such as a discount or BOGO (buy one get one free). Some users might not receive any offer during certain weeks.

Not all users receive the same offer, and that is the challenge to solve with this data set.

Your task is to combine transaction, demographic and offer data to determine which demographic groups respond best to which offer type. This data set is a simplified version of the real Starbucks app because the underlying simulator only has one product whereas Starbucks actually sells dozens of products.

Every offer has a validity period before the offer expires. As an example, a BOGO offer might be valid for only 5 days. You'll see in the data set that informational offers have a validity period even though these ads are merely providing information about a product; for example, if an informational offer has 7 days of validity, you can assume the customer is feeling the influence of the offer for 7 days after receiving the advertisement.

You'll be given transactional data showing user purchases made on the app including the timestamp of purchase and the amount of money spent on a purchase. This transactional data also has a record for each offer that a user receives as well as a record for when a user actually views the offer. There are also records for when a user completes an offer.

Keep in mind as well that someone using the app might make a purchase through the app without having received an offer or seen an offer.

Example¶

To give an example, a user could receive a discount offer buy 10 dollars get 2 off on Monday. The offer is valid for 10 days from receipt. If the customer accumulates at least 10 dollars in purchases during the validity period, the customer completes the offer.

However, there are a few things to watch out for in this data set. Customers do not opt into the offers that they receive; in other words, a user can receive an offer, never actually view the offer, and still complete the offer. For example, a user might receive the "buy 10 dollars get 2 dollars off offer", but the user never opens the offer during the 10 day validity period. The customer spends 15 dollars during those ten days. There will be an offer completion record in the data set; however, the customer was not influenced by the offer because the customer never viewed the offer.

Query¶

  • Which channel more contributes to customer response?
  • Average response time.
  • Success-fail distribution by gender.

Data Sets¶

The data is contained in three files:

  • portfolio.json - containing offer ids and meta data about each offer (duration, type, etc.)
  • profile.json - demographic data for each customer
  • transcript.json - records for transactions, offers received, offers viewed, and offers completed

def remove_outlier(df, col):
    """
    input: df, and col
    return: removed dataframe
    """
    mean = df[col].mean()
    std = df[col].std()
    q1 = df[col].quantile(0.25)
    q3 = df[col].quantile(0.75)
    IQR = q3 - q1 
    removed_outlier = df[(df[col] > q1 - 1.5 * IQR) & (df[col] < q3 + 1.5 * IQR)]
    return removed_outlier

Portfolio Datasets¶

portfolio.json

  • id (string) - offer id
  • offer_type (string) - type of offer ie BOGO, discount, informational
  • difficulty (int) - minimum required spend to complete an offer
  • reward (int) - reward given for completing an offer
  • duration (int) - time for offer to be open, in days
  • channels (list of strings)

Profile Datasets¶

profile.json

  • age (int) - age of the customer
  • became_member_on (int) - date when customer created an app account
  • gender (str) - gender of the customer (note some entries contain 'O' for other rather than M or F)
  • id (str) - customer id
  • income (float) - customer's income

Transcript Datasets¶

----- effective offers -------

  • offer received --> offer viewed --> transaction --> offer completed (BOGB/discount offers)
  • offer received --> offer viewed --> transaction (information offers)

----- ineffective offers -----

  • offer received --> offer viewed !--> transaction

----- offers are received but no action taken -----

  • offer received !-->

transcript.json

  • event (str) - record description (ie transaction, offer received, offer viewed, etc.)
  • person (str) - customer id
  • time (int) - time in hours since start of test. The data begins at time t=0
  • value - (dict of strings) - either an offer id or transaction amount depending on the record

# separate value column which includes offer__id and amount
id_amount_reward = json_normalize(transcript['value'])
id_amount_reward['offer_id'] = np.where(id_amount_reward['offer_id'].notnull(), id_amount_reward['offer_id'], id_amount_reward['offer id'])
id_amount_reward.drop('offer id', axis = 1, inplace = True)
transcript = pd.concat([transcript, id_amount_reward], axis = 1)
transcript.drop('value', axis = 1, inplace = True)

## show event by. time series after the test starts
from collections import defaultdict
df = transcript.merge(portfolio.drop('reward', axis = 1), on = 'offer_id', how = 'outer')
received_time = transcript[transcript['event'] == 'offer received']['time']
time_series = defaultdict(int)

for t in df['time'].unique():
    time_series[t] = 0 
for t in received_time:
    time_series[t] += 1
received_time = pd.Series(time_series)


### plot time series
plt.figure(figsize = (8, 5))
labels = ['offer completed', 'transaction', 'offer viewed', 'offer received']
for label in labels:
    if label != 'offer received':
        df.groupby('event')['time'].value_counts().sort_index()[label].plot()
    if label == 'offer received':
        received_time.plot()
plt.title('Transcript event', fontsize = 16)
plt.ylabel('Counts', fontsize = 14)
plt.xlabel('Time(hour)', fontsize = 14)
plt.legend(labels)
plt.show()

def get_success():
    
    """
    Input: offer_id
    Return: successed dataFrame of the specific offer_id
    
    """
    offer_ids = portfolio.offer_id
    
    # merge received and viewed dataframe 
    receive_view_df = pd.merge(offer_received, offer_viewed, on = ["personal_id", "offer_id"], how = 'inner')
    
    
    # merge receive_view_df and completed dataframe
    receive_view_complete = pd.merge(receive_view_df, offer_completed, on = ["personal_id", "offer_id"], how = 'inner')
    # set success_df
    success_df = pd.DataFrame()
    
    for offer_id in offer_ids: 
        try: 
        
            # extract the specific offer_id dataframe
            df = receive_view_complete[receive_view_complete['offer_id'] == offer_id]
            
            
            
            # get the duration 
            duration = float(portfolio[portfolio["offer_id"] == offer_id].duration * 24)
    
    
            # set the expiration dates 
            times = df.received_time + duration
            df = df[df['completed_time'] <= times].drop_duplicates()
            
            # set the expiration dates with the different dataframe length
            times = df.received_time + duration
            df = df[df['viewed_time'] <= times].drop_duplicates()
            df = df.query("received_time <= viewed_time <= completed_time").drop_duplicates()
            df = df.sort_values(by = ['personal_id', 'offer_id', 'received_time', 'viewed_time','completed_time']).drop_duplicates(['personal_id', 'offer_id','received_time'], keep = 'first')
            df = df.sort_values(by = ['personal_id', 'offer_id', 'viewed_time', 'completed_time']).drop_duplicates(subset = ['personal_id', 'offer_id','viewed_time'], keep = 'last')

            success_df = pd.concat([success_df, df], axis = 0)
        except:
            pass

    index = success_df.index
    
    return success_df.loc[list(index)].drop_duplicates()

def visualize_success(offer_id):
    results = subject_df[subject_df['offer_id'] == offer_id]
    result = results.groupby(["success"])['gender'].value_counts() 

    labels = ['Male', 'Female','other']
    success_ = result[1.0]
    fail_ = result[0.0]


    x = np.arange(len(labels))  # the label locations
    width = 0.4  # the width of the bars

    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize = (8, 6))
    rects1 = ax.bar(x - width/2, success_ , width, label='success', color = 'black')
    rects2 = ax.bar(x + width/2, fail_, width, label='fail', color = 'gray')

    # Add some text for labels, title and custom x-axis tick labels, etc.
    ax.set_ylabel('frequency', fontsize = 12)
    ax.set_title(f'{offer_id}', fontsize = 16)
    ax.set_xticks(x)
    ax.set_xticklabels(labels)
    ax.legend(fontsize = 12)


    def autolabel(rects):
        """Attach a text label above each bar in *rects*, displaying its height."""
        for rect in rects:
            height = rect.get_height()
            ax.annotate('{}'.format(height),
                        xy=(rect.get_x() + rect.get_width() / 2, height),
                        xytext=(0, 3),  # 3 points vertical offset
                        textcoords="offset points",
                        ha='center', va='bottom')

    autolabel(rects1)
    autolabel(rects2)
    fig.tight_layout()

    plt.show()

def show_channel_dist(offer_type):
    """
    Input: offer_type: String 
    Output: 
    
    this functions display channel frequency of the specific offer_type
    
    """
    tools = subject_df.query(f"offer_type == '{offer_type}'")[['gender', 'success', 'web', 'email', 'mobile', 'social']].groupby(['success','gender']).sum()
    (tools/tools.sum()).plot(kind = 'bar', figsize = (9, 6), title = f"offer_type: {offer_type}")
    plt.show()

def distribution(offer_type, income_or_age):
    """
    Input: offer_type: String , income_or_age: String
    Output: 
    
    this function displays distributions of income or age 
    """
    df = subject_df[subject_df['offer_type'] == offer_type]
    success_income = df[df.success == 1][income_or_age]
    fail_income = df[df.success == 0][income_or_age]
    sns.distplot(success_income[success_income.notna()],label='success', color = 'blue')
    sns.distplot(fail_income[fail_income.notna()],label='fail', color = 'red')
    plt.legend()
    plt.show()
    
    display(df.groupby("gender")[income_or_age].describe())

def t_test(income_or_age, offer_type = None):
    """
    Input: offer_type: String, income_or_age: String
    output: 
    
    """
    data = subject_df.groupby('gender')[income_or_age].describe().reset_index()
    
    if offer_type:
        data = subject_df.query(f"offer_type == '{offer_type}'").groupby('gender')[income_or_age].describe().reset_index()
    F = data[data['gender'] == 'F']
    M = data[data['gender'] == 'M']
    O = data[data['gender'] == 'O']
    # def t_test(data)
    # calculate standard errors
    seM, seF = float(M["std"])/np.sqrt(float(M["count"])), float(F["std"])/np.sqrt(float(F["count"]))
    sed = np.sqrt(seM**2.0 + seF**2.0)
    t_stat = (float(M["mean"]) - float(F["mean"])) / sed
    # degrees of freedom
    df = float(M["count"]) + float(F["count"]) - 2
    alpha = 0.05
    # calculate the critical value
    cv = t.ppf(1.0 - alpha, df)
    p = (1.0 - t.cdf(abs(t_stat), df)) * 2.0
    print('t=%.3f, df=%d, cv=%.3f, p=%.3f' % (t_stat, df, cv, p))
    # interpret via critical value
    if abs(t_stat) <= cv:
        print('Accept null hypothesis that the means are equal.')
    else:
        print('Reject the null hypothesis that the means are equal.')
    # interpret via p-value
    if p > alpha:
        print('Accept null hypothesis that the means are equal.')
    else:
        print('Reject the null hypothesis that the means are equal.')

## replace Nan of income 
gender = ['M','F','O']
for g in gender:
    mean_ = round(clean_df.query(f"gender == '{g}'").income.mean())
    std_ = round(clean_df.query(f"gender == '{g}'").income.std())
    len_ = len(clean_df[(clean_df['income'].isna()) & (clean_df['gender'] == f'{g}')].index)
    min_ = round(clean_df.query(f"gender == '{g}'").income.min())
    max_ = round(clean_df.query(f"gender == '{g}'").income.max())
    print(g, mean_, std_, len_)
    lower, upper = min_, max_
    mu, sigma = mean_, std_
    choices = stats.truncnorm(
    (lower - mu) / sigma, (upper - mu) / sigma, loc=mu, scale=sigma)
    choices = choices.rvs(len_)
    clean_df.loc[list(clean_df[(clean_df['gender'] == f'{g}') & (clean_df['income'].isna())].index), 'income'] = clean_df.loc[list(clean_df[(clean_df['gender'] == f'{g}') & (clean_df['income'].isna())].index), 'income'].apply(lambda _: np.random.choice(choices))

import scipy.stats as stats
## replace NaN of age 

gender = ['M','F','O']
for g in gender:
    mean_ = round(clean_df.query(f"gender == '{g}'").age.mean())
    std_ = round(clean_df.query(f"gender == '{g}'").age.std())
    len_ = len(clean_df[(clean_df['age'].isna()) & (clean_df['gender'] == f'{g}')].index)
    min_ = round(clean_df.query(f"gender == '{g}'").age.min())
    max_ = round(clean_df.query(f"gender == '{g}'").age.max())
    print(g, mean_, std_, len_)
    lower, upper = min_, max_
    mu, sigma = mean_, std_
    choices = stats.truncnorm(
    (lower - mu) / sigma, (upper - mu) / sigma, loc=mu, scale=sigma)
    choices = choices.rvs(len_)
    clean_df.loc[list(clean_df[(clean_df['gender'] == f'{g}') & (clean_df['age'].isna())].index), 'age'] = clean_df.loc[list(clean_df[(clean_df['gender'] == f'{g}') & (clean_df['age'].isna())].index), 'age'].apply(lambda _: np.random.choice(choices))

Report¶

  • female members are more likely to complete offers than males.
  • female members are older than male and have higher income.
  • in the bogo offer, web and social channels more contributes to success; in the discount offer, mobile and social chennels more impacts on success.
